Most of the holiday rental services on the web are just the "go-between" or the "classified" portion of the newspaper. They take no responsibility for the truth or correctness of the ads that are for auction on their sites. So, do your homework by looking into making telephone calls, talking to the owner and asking specific questions. Make sure you feel comfortable with the answers, otherwise, move on to the next rental, there are many.

If you aren't comfortable with the whole renter/owner thing, there is a different way to rent a vacation home. Some companies exist that strictly buy and rent out homes to vacationers. They offer a bit more security so that you feel you're truly getting what you bargained for (although there is nothing ever 100% certified). Additionally, sometimes these agencies will give you cancellation insurance. In other words, if you cancel before arriving, they might be in a position to refund some of your deposit or payment rather than keeping it as being most owners do if a cancellation occurs. With a few agencies you will find that you have to pay a greater price than going directly to an owner. This is the way the agencies make their profits. There will always be benefits and drawbacks to every scenario. Ensure you know which one works well with you.

Just how much must i expect to pay?

This can be a tough question to answer. The number you pay is determined by what country or state you are visiting, number of days you're staying, and type of house you're renting. Some owners offer package deals including tickets or sightseeing events along with the rental, others include bonus days should you stay for any certain period of time. There are other owners who may offer free or add-on house cleaning service together with your stay although some go to great efforts to ensure you have everything you need, even additional items like a crib, highchair or wheelchair. Each vacation rental is going to be entirely diverse from the next. The best choice after choosing your destination is to review multiple rentals to find out which is better suitable for your needs and overall budget.

Are there any hidden fees?

Hidden fees usually only emerge once you have arrived. These could include extra for phone calls, home cleaning service, extra person fees, excess heat and air-conditioning bills, pet deposit, computer access... etc. Again, be extremely thorough when interviewing who owns your prospective holiday rental. Inquire about any "extra" fees, or if the house is "all-inclusive". Do you have free use of all the pantry and foods? How about the laundry supplies? All utilities? It never hurts to inquire about!

